<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Sun, 22 Feb 2004 00:43:57 -0600
From: Jack Steinmann <jsteinmann@CLYNCH.COM>
Source: Reuters Fri 20 Feb 2004 11:07 PM ET [edited]
<http://www.reuters.com/newsArticle.jhtml?type=worldNews&storyID=4407100>

Anthrax Shots Made Australian Troops Sick - Report
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Australian troops headed for Iraq in 2003 received compulsory anthrax shots
but were not told that troops sent earlier to Afghanistan had suffered
severe side effects from the vaccine, an Australian daily said on Saturday.
The Australian newspaper said defense documents received under freedom of
information laws showed that the defense force had had problems with the
vaccine back in November 2001. "The entire anthrax vaccination program for
the military deployment to Afghanistan was secretly suspended," said the
newspaper.
It said the program was halted for 2 months after 75 percent of the 1500
Afghan deployment in 2002, including elite special forces who were to
engage in fierce fighting with the Taliban, fell ill. The newspaper said a
defense doctor's briefing note to the then chief of the Australian Defense
Force, Admiral Chris Barrie, said "(defense) has reported a very high rate
of adverse events being suffered by personnel."
The note went on to say that the side effects from the anthrax shots "could
be operationally significant if the units concerned received their
vaccinations after being deployed." [Reported] side effects included
"swelling and pain severe enough for (troops) not to be able to use the
affected arm, and flu-like illness severe enough for some personnel to
require sick leave for 24-48 hours."
"All units involved in this vaccination campaign have been told to cease
use of the...anthrax vaccine until further notice," said the internal
defense document quoted by the newspaper.
A spokeswoman for Australian Defense Minister Robert Hill told Reuters all
troops deployed to Iraq had been informed of the full extent of the anthrax
side effects.
At the time of the troop deployment to Iraq, Hill said the vaccination
shots, which were compulsory for the 2000 military personnel sent, were
safe and had anthrax shots himself to show he had confidence in the safety
of the vaccinations. Around 40 Australians troops sent to the Middle East
refused to have the shots and were sent home. Many were not told of the
anthrax shots until they were sailing to the Gulf.
At the time Britain allowed its troops go to the Gulf without the anthrax
shots as long as they signed a legal waiver.
The United States led Australian and British forces into Iraq in 2003,
accusing Iraq of developing weapons of mass destruction including
biological agents such as anthrax.
[I passed the above report to Col. John Grabenstein. - Mod.MHJ]
