[2]
Date: Mon 23 Feb 2004 12:22 PM
From: Col. John D. Grabenstein <John.Grabenstein@otsg.amedd.army.mil>

Comment:
Several recent news reports from Australia succeed in raising alarms about
anthrax vaccine again, while offering little in the way of information.
Readers would infer that 38 percent or 75 percent of anthrax-vaccinated
people (depending on the news article) suffered side effects, but which
side effects had which rates and of what duration? The numbers offered in
the articles are not specific enough to be useful in evaluating the
Australian safety experience. The authors seem to have mixed descriptions
of unusual swelling cases with statistics about common events.
The American anthrax vaccine has been given to about 1.1 million people
since 1998; the British anthrax vaccine somewhat fewer. These anthrax
vaccines are known commodities. An adverse event seen in 1/3 or 3/4 of
recipients would be patently obvious among a million people. American
troops and clinicians have indeed seen reactions occurring in 1/3 of
vaccinees: redness, tenderness, swelling, headache, malaise; in short, the
adverse events seen after any vaccination. In the American experience,
large-magnitude swelling occurs in 1 -or 2 percent of recipients. The
National Academy of Sciences (America's premier civilian scientific
advisory group) reviewed the safety of anthrax vaccine, considering over a
dozen safety studies of various scientific designs and hearing personally
from people who believe they had been harmed by anthrax vaccine. The NAS
conclusion: Anthrax vaccine has a side-effect profile like that of other
vaccines given to adults. Table 4-1 in that report provides a convenient
review of adverse events for other adult vaccines.
<http://www.nap.edu/catalog/10310.html>
A typhoid vaccine widely used internationally notes in the package insert
that 98 percent of recipients report side effects. How can regulators allow
such a vaccine to be marketed? Set the logical parameters to count anybody
who has any symptom after vaccination, and you will count most of the
recipients. Shots hurt.
My understanding of the Australian Government's actions was that it
developed its anthrax-vaccination policies based on tactical situations,
with no need to modify its policies due to adverse-event considerations.
Obviously, the Australian Government would want to speak for itself on the
matter. A July 2003 statement from them appears at
<http://www.defence.gov.au/dpe/dhs/infocentre/anthrax/i-anthrax.htm>.
Because the recent Australian experience involves the British-made vaccine,
the British manufacturer should have an opportunity to speak as well.
The antidotes for sensationalism are facts, details that are missing from
these recent headlines:
- report what fraction of vaccine recipients reported which symptoms;
- set an objective definition for serious (e.g., swelling > 12 cm) and
report the fraction for whom that applies; and
- name any events that happen more often among vaccinated people than
unvaccinated people.
In short, let's bring the scientific method to bear on questions of vaccine
safety.
Naturally, good scientists and clinicians need to keep eyes and ears open
to unexpected findings. The Australians have probably identified the
pattern of injection-site reactions and malaise that other users of anthrax
vaccine are already familiar with. The troops deserve to have this
assumption confirmed. We all need more information than what is provided in
these short news articles before concluding that something new is afoot.
---
Col. John Grabenstein, RPh, PhD
Deputy Director for Military Vaccines,
Office of the US Army Surgeon General
Falls Church, VA USA
<http://www.anthrax.mil>www.anthrax.mil>
